# Step-by-Step Commands — FTP Exposure Lab

Run all commands ONLY inside an isolated lab
and ONLY against systems you own or are authorized to test.

Replace:
<LAB_TARGET_IP> with the target IP
<IFACE> with your network interface (eth0, wlan0, etc.)

---

## Step 1 — Create evidence directory
```bash
TS=$(date +%Y%m%d_%H%M%S)
mkdir -p evidence/$TS


Step 2 — Record lab context
bash
Copy code
echo "Target: <LAB_TARGET_IP>" > evidence/$TS/context.txt
echo "Attacker: $(uname -a)" >> evidence/$TS/context.txt


Step 3 — Verify connectivity
bash
Copy code
ping -c 2 <LAB_TARGET_IP>


Step 4 — Full port and service discovery
bash
Copy code
nmap -sV -p- <LAB_TARGET_IP> -oN evidence/$TS/nmap_full.txt


Step 5 — FTP service discovery (port 21)
bash
Copy code
nmap -sV -p 21 <LAB_TARGET_IP> -oN evidence/$TS/nmap_ftp_21.txt


Step 6 — FTP enumeration (non-invasive scripts)
bash
Copy code
nmap --script ftp-* -p 21 <LAB_TARGET_IP> -oN evidence/$TS/nmap_ftp_scripts.txt


Step 7 — Vulnerability research reference (local database)
bash
Copy code
searchsploit ftp > evidence/$TS/searchsploit_ftp.txt


Step 8 — Optional packet capture for evidence
bash
Copy code
sudo tcpdump -i <IFACE> host <LAB_TARGET_IP> -w evidence/$TS/ftp_lab_capture.pcap
Stop capture with:
bash
Copy code
Ctrl + C


Step 9 — Create summary notes
bash
Copy code
echo "FTP Exposure Lab Summary" > evidence/$TS/SUMMARY.md
echo "Target: <LAB_TARGET_IP>" >> evidence/$TS/SUMMARY.md
echo "Findings: Exposed FTP service increases attack surface." >> evidence/$TS/SUMMARY.md
echo "Recommendation: Remove or replace FTP, restrict access, monitor scans." >> evidence/$TS/SUMMARY.md


Step 10 — Review collected evidence
bash
Copy code
ls -lah evidence/$TS


End of Lab
All outputs are stored inside:
evidence/<timestamp>/


cat evidence/$TS/nmap_ftp_21.txt
